{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Measures current flow in Amps (A).",
      "misconception": "Thinking it measures voltage or potential difference."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference between two points.",
      "anchor": "Measures potential difference in Volts (V).",
      "misconception": "Believing it measures the flow of electrons rather than the pressure pushing them."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical resistance of a component or circuit.",
      "anchor": "Measures resistance in Ohms (Ω).",
      "misconception": "Attempting to use it on a live circuit; it must only be used on dead circuits to avoid damage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate of electrical power being used at a specific moment.",
      "anchor": "Measures instantaneous power in Watts (W).",
      "misconception": "Confusing it with an energy meter that tracks usage over time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time.",
      "anchor": "Measures energy consumption in kilowatt-hours (kWh).",
      "misconception": "Thinking it measures the same thing as a Wattmeter; energy is power multiplied by time."
    },
    {
      "term": "Multimeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A single test instrument that combines several measurement functions, typically voltage, current, and resistance.",
      "anchor": "A versatile tool for measuring multiple electrical quantities.",
      "misconception": "Assuming it is a single-purpose tool rather than a combination of specific instruments."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ammeter for current",
    "Voltmeter for voltage",
    "Ohmmeter for resistance",
    "Wattmeter for power",
    "Energy meter for consumption",
    "Multimeter for multiple functions"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Confusing power (Watts) with energy (kWh).",
    "Using an ohmmeter on a live circuit.",
    "Believing a multimeter automatically selects the correct measurement mode without user input."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Measuring Fundamental Quantities",
      "objective": "Identify the correct instruments for measuring voltage, current, and resistance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely and accurately on site, you must select the correct instrument for the specific electrical quantity you are testing. When you need to measure the flow of electrons through a conductor, you use an Ammeter, which provides a reading in Amps (A). If you are checking the electrical pressure or potential difference between two points, you use a Voltmeter to get a reading in Volts (V).",
        "For measuring how much a component opposes the flow of current, you use an Ohmmeter to find the resistance in Ohms (Ω). A critical rule for any electrician is that an Ohmmeter must only be used on 'dead' (de-energised) circuits; attempting to test a live circuit with one will likely damage the meter and pose a safety risk.",
        "While many modern electricians carry a Multimeter, remember that this is simply a combined tool. It does not automatically know what you are testing; you must manually select the correct function—Volts, Amps, or Ohms—to ensure the internal circuitry is configured correctly for the measurement."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring flow (Amps), pressure (Volts), or opposition (Ohms)."
    },
    {
      "key": "202-2b-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the correct instruments for measuring electrical power and energy consumption.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Beyond basic current and voltage, we must measure how much work electricity is doing. Power is the instantaneous rate of energy use at a specific moment. To measure this, we use a Wattmeter, which shows the power in Watts (W). This is useful for checking if a motor or heater is operating at its designed rating.",
        "Energy is distinct from power because it accounts for time. It is the total amount of power consumed over a duration. To track this, we use an Energy Meter, commonly referred to as a kilowatt-hour (kWh) meter. This is the standard instrument used by utility companies for billing purposes.",
        "A helpful way to remember the difference is the car analogy: a Wattmeter is like a speedometer showing your speed at one moment, whereas an Energy Meter is like an odometer showing the total distance you have travelled. You cannot use a standard Wattmeter to determine a monthly electricity bill, just as you cannot use an Energy Meter to see the exact power spike when a machine first starts up."
      ],
      "hint": "One meter measures the 'rate' at a single moment, while the other measures 'total usage' over time."
    }
  ]
}

