{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Comprehensive System Diagnostic",
    "objective": "Synthesize the selection of instruments for voltage, resistance, power, and energy within a single diagnostic scenario while applying safety constraints.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "When troubleshooting a system, you don't just grab one tool. You need to understand whether you are measuring a state (voltage), a physical property (resistance), a rate of work (power), or a cumulative total (energy).",
      "Each requires a specific instrument or a specific mode on your multimeter. Furthermore, you must distinguish between 'live' functional tests and 'dead' continuity or resistance tests to protect both yourself and your equipment.",
      "Remember the distinction between instantaneous rates (like a speedometer) and cumulative totals (like an odometer) when dealing with power and energy."
    ],
    "questionText": "A client claims their industrial heater is underperforming and expensive to run. You are tasked with the following: 1) Measure the electrical pressure at the heater terminals while running. 2) Check the heating element's opposition to current while the power is isolated. 3) Measure the instantaneous rate of work the heater is doing to see if it matches its rating. 4) Record the total energy consumed over a full 8-hour shift. Identify the four specific instruments required for these tasks and state which specific measurement would damage the instrument if the circuit remained live.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "1. Voltmeter (for electrical pressure/voltage)",
      "2. Ohmmeter (for opposition/resistance)",
      "3. Wattmeter (for instantaneous rate of work/power)",
      "4. Energy Meter or kWh Meter (for total consumption over time)",
      "The Ohmmeter measurement must be performed on a dead circuit; using it on a live circuit will damage the instrument."
    ],
    "hint": "Match the quantity (Voltage, Resistance, Power, Energy) to the meter. Only one of these measures a physical property of the component itself rather than the electricity flowing through it."
  }
}

